PUH-BrianMartell Soliton Stability Equations — Understandable Derivation In PUH v25, particles are torsional solitons — self-reinforcing standing waves that maintain shape because lattice nonlinearity (torsional tension ξ) exactly balances dispersion (ripple spreading). Simple picture: •  Linear lattice: Ripples spread → no stable particles. •  Nonlinear ξ: Higher tension in dense regions → compresses wave back. •  Balance: Soliton velocity v_s such that dispersion = nonlinearity → stable localized knot (mass). Core equation (1D torsional analog of sine-Gordon/KdV): ∂²u/∂t² = v_ripple² ∂²u/∂x² - ω₀² sin(u) u displacement (twist angle), ω₀ natural frequency from ξ stiffness. Soliton solution u = 4 arctan(exp((x - v t)/√(1 - v²/v_ripple²))) — stable for v < v_ripple. Stability: Energy minimum in nonlinear potential — perturbation decays.
